                <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00/2782: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morales</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-12-17T14:00:00-06:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 17, 1923—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>I have been reliably informed that the Government intends to declare a state of
                    martial law throughout the country within a few days for the purpose of
                    dominating the situation and maintaining peace up until Congress convenes at
                    which time the decree establishing martial law will be revoked.</p>
                <p>A declaration of martial law at this time may precipitate the revolution as the
                    action of the Government will be interpreted by Carias as hostile to him and his
                    party.</p>
                <p>The contents of the Department’s telegram of December 15, 6 p.m. were conveyed
                    informally to Carias this morning. Repeated to Salvador and Nicaragua.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morales</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
